BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:History of Generative Music: The Ancients
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260409T220000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260410T000000Z
UID:69a1fe408089f23c675eaefd@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Long before computers or artificial intelligence\, people were
  creating systems that made music on their own - from wind chimes that pla
 yed melodies shaped by the breeze to water-driven instruments in ancient g
 ardens. These early innovations laid the groundwork for ideas that compose
 rs and technologists still use today.\nIn this session\, you'll explore th
 e surprising origins of generative music in the ancient world\, discover t
 he physical and intellectual mechanisms behind these early inventions\, an
 d learn how these centuries-old concepts connect directly to modern music 
 production and AI.\nDrop-in\, no registration required.\nThis program is p
 art of the Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, whic
 h is designed to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge a
 nd creative skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music product
 ion and learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music
 . For more information and a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesid
 ent\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1fe408089f23c675eaefd
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Create a DJ Set with AI Tools for Teens
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260418T180000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260418T200000Z
UID:69a1ff7a491b809c6f1cfc8f@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Ever wonder how DJs create seamless mixes that keep a dance fl
 oor moving? What if you could build your own DJ set from scratch using art
 ificial intelligence?\nJoin us for a hands-on demonstration/workshop where
  you'll use AI to generate original beat-based music\, then learn how to b
 reak it down into stems\, loops\, and sections\, and then reassemble them 
 into a dynamic set you can perform live. No prior music or programming exp
 erience is required.\nRegistration is required.\nThis program is part of t
 he Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is des
 igned to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creat
 ive skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and 
 learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For mo
 re information and a full list of programs\, visit tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1ff7a491b809c6f1cfc8f
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Music Copyright and Ethics in the AI Era
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260424T220000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260425T000000Z
UID:69a2002c491b809c6f1cfcda@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:When you use AI to create music\, who actually owns it? Can a 
 melody generated by a machine infringe on someone else's copyright? As AI 
 tools become more accessible\, these questions are more relevant than ever
  - and the answers aren't always straightforward.\nIn this session\, you'l
 l get a plain-language breakdown of how music copyright works\, what the r
 ules are around sampling\, and how these long-standing principles apply to
  AI-generated music. You'll also hear about landmark legal cases - both su
 rprising victories and cautionary tales - including real-world examples fr
 om a working composer's own career.\nDrop-in\, no registration required.\n
 This program is part of the Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Productio
 n) program\, which is designed to help beginner and intermediate learners 
 build knowledge and creative skills and get hands-on with current AI tools
  in music production and learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of
  generative music. For more information and a full list of programs\, visi
 t tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a2002c491b809c6f1cfcda
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:History of Generative Music: The Early Modern Era
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260430T200000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260430T220000Z
UID:69a200ef1e64afd01e5e909d@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:The twentieth century brought radical new ideas about what mus
 ic could be - from compositions determined by coin tosses to pieces that r
 earranged themselves with every performance. Pioneering composers began us
 ing chance\, repetition\, and early electronics to challenge everything au
 diences thought they knew about music.\nIn this session\, you'll explore h
 ow early modern composers pushed the boundaries of generative music\, disc
 over the creative and technical mechanisms behind their experiments\, and 
 learn how their breakthroughs paved the way for the AI music tools we use 
 today.\nDrop-in\, no registration required.\nThis program is part of the I
 nnovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designe
 d to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative 
 skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and lear
 n about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more i
 nformation and a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a200ef1e64afd01e5e909d
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
